				\begin{document}$${\rm{T}}={(1+\frac{188.5}{{R}_{s}}\frac{{\sigma }_{op}}{{\sigma }_{dc}})}^{-2}$$\end{document}where T stands for the transmittance, Rs refers to the sheet resistance, σdc is the dc conductivity, and σop is the optical conductivity. By fitting the T ~ Rs curves with eq. (1), the σdc/σop ratio could be estimated, which presents the figure of merit (FOM) of TEs. In principles, the higher FOM value indicates the better TE performance. The FOM of the pure Cu NWs is determined to be 111 and that of Cu@graphene NWs gets 121. The improvement of performance after graphene encapsulation appears mainly on the right hand side to the turning point, which could be attributed to the modification of Cu surface and the formation of Cu-graphene interface.
